body.body: During manufacture, grease is used to install the dust seals and oil to lubricate the piston seals.
This means a residue of oil and/or grease can be hidden in cavities during the manufacturing process.

When riding the motorcycle the up and down movement of the forks generates heat, therefore the grease or oil's viscosity changes and the manufacturing residue can become visible on the outside of the fork.
Triumph and the suspension manufacturer consider this as a normal condition and not a manufacturing defect.
Do not use household cleaning products, bleach, detergents containing any kind of solvent to clean the forks.
Do not spray water directly into the adjuster knobs, electrical components or connectors.
Using aggressive cleaning agents or detergents will cause premature wear and or damage to the motorcycle.
Inspect the front fork components for damage or fluid leaks.
Using the table below evaluate the condition of the front forks.
Clean off oil residue, refer to
Thin oil film containing dirt or dust
Clean off oil and dust residue, clean the fork seals, refer to the Service Manual and return to customer.
A film of oil including a droplet running down the inner tube

Using a method that will not scratch or damage the polished surfaces, clean the external parts with a proprietary cleaning agent and a soft lint free cloth.
Lift components like bump rubbers or rubber boots and clean all areas and cavities.
Make sure that any dirt or debris is removed.
Wipe off and dry with a clean cloth.
Inspect the damper rod for corrosion and/or pitting.
Carry out a road test and check for fluid leaks, refer to the table above.
